1
00:00:01,230 --> 00:00:16,690
So, in this experiment we have the same coil that was shown in the first video, only now we've tinkered with it a bit, rewound the inductor and added a couple of things.

2
00:00:18,870 --> 00:00:33,550
We have a milliammeter, but in this case its readings won't be correct, we'll just use it to indicate current by the division scale.

3
00:00:34,490 --> 00:00:50,790
For this DC milliammeter to respond to AC current, with this fast diode here we'll cut off one half-cycle and direct the current in one direction.

4
00:00:53,210 --> 00:00:59,610
We're also using a digital signal generator and a digital oscilloscope.

5
00:01:00,470 --> 00:01:08,370
Here we see the signal generator is currently outputting half a volt, peak-to-peak amplitude.

6
00:01:08,770 --> 00:01:16,570
It outputs from these probe ends, and it goes to the coil's inductor.

7
00:01:17,110 --> 00:01:33,130
At the output we see an amplitude of around 440-400 mV, that is, practically the same.

8
00:01:34,930 --> 00:01:41,550
We confirm that this kind of coil is not a step-down transformer.

9
00:01:43,610 --> 00:01:48,990
Here the inductor is half the wire length of what's wound here.

10
00:01:49,670 --> 00:01:57,210
So it turns out, in addition, here it should have, accordingly, fewer turns here, more on the primary coil.

11
00:01:57,370 --> 00:02:02,270
In theory we should get a step-up transformer, but that doesn't happen.

12
00:02:04,270 --> 00:02:05,250
Let's keep watching.

13
00:02:06,310 --> 00:02:18,990
We measure the current in divisions using our milliammeter, which the generator is now feeding directly.

14
00:02:19,190 --> 00:02:35,290
For this we disconnect the probe from the generator and attach the clip to it, which will go to the ammeter.

15
00:02:38,670 --> 00:02:40,070
Hooked up.

16
00:02:40,070 --> 00:02:43,210
We lock in the readings.

17
00:02:46,230 --> 00:02:50,230
Right now we have 14 divisions,

18
00:02:53,710 --> 00:03:04,550
accordingly, 14 divisions of current at half-volt amplitude.

19
00:03:07,930 --> 00:03:13,890
We return the signal generator back to the inductor.

20
00:03:15,170 --> 00:03:16,370
Hooking it up.

21
00:03:30,050 --> 00:03:31,130
Hooked up.

22
00:03:31,250 --> 00:03:34,130
There, we see the output amplitude is back.

23
00:03:34,890 --> 00:03:44,570
We take the amplitude from the bank of capacitors that's connected through the slider to the secondary coil's output.

24
00:03:45,730 --> 00:03:54,510
Now we move our milliammeter to the output in short-circuit mode.

25
00:03:54,690 --> 00:04:00,610
We attach one probe, attach the other.

26
00:04:02,830 --> 00:04:15,350
And we see the current readings match 23.5, a tiny bit more than the division.

27
00:04:17,390 --> 00:04:19,370
Why is this happening?

28
00:04:20,390 --> 00:04:22,470
What kind of tuning is this?

29
00:04:23,070 --> 00:04:28,070
Why is the coil giving more than what's being sent to it?

30
00:04:29,230 --> 00:04:38,510
I repeat, we're taking readings using a sine wave, so there's no debate about whether there are signals with steep edges here.

31
00:04:39,510 --> 00:04:41,670
You could of course do it with this too.

32
00:04:41,750 --> 00:04:44,970
Let's switch to a square wave, for example.

33
00:04:46,130 --> 00:04:58,010
We see the current has gone up even more, from which we'll understand that this coil will be driven by a steep-edged signal.

34
00:04:59,030 --> 00:05:00,930
Switching back to sine.

35
00:05:03,910 --> 00:05:19,670
So what is it that we did here that made the output current in short-circuit mode exceed the current supplied by the generator, while the output voltage practically matches the voltage supplied by the generator?

36
00:05:23,410 --> 00:05:24,530
The answer is this.

37
00:05:24,670 --> 00:05:44,710
We synchronized this coil of ours, through geometric proportions, wire cross-sections, wire lengths, with the natural vibrations that exist in our space.

38
00:05:45,670 --> 00:05:47,570
At this frequency.

39
00:05:48,850 --> 00:05:57,110
You don't need to memorize this frequency, for each region it'll be individual, and specifically for each coil.

40
00:05:58,230 --> 00:06:04,310
For that, these frequencies are searched out and specifically tuned, and coils are built for them.

41
00:06:05,670 --> 00:06:08,130
So now we'll show what's happening for us.

42
00:06:08,270 --> 00:06:10,770
This is the carrier signal at this frequency.

43
00:06:12,090 --> 00:06:15,710
We zoom out the trace per division.

44
00:06:16,370 --> 00:06:19,610
Right here it says "time" for us.

45
00:06:21,470 --> 00:06:23,050
Compressing the trace.

46
00:06:24,410 --> 00:06:28,090
We see a low-frequency component appearing in our spectrum.

47
00:06:28,090 --> 00:06:30,150
Next.

48
00:06:32,810 --> 00:06:38,010
Here we can lock in the amplitude modulation.

49
00:06:38,750 --> 00:06:55,850
And this means that this coil is being synchronized with an external frequency, which amplitude-modulates its oscillations initiated by our signal generator.

50
00:06:55,890 --> 00:06:59,450
We can take a closer look at what this is.

51
00:07:04,580 --> 00:07:08,360
This is this type of traveling wave.

52
00:07:09,260 --> 00:07:11,040
This is the first synchronization.

53
00:07:12,940 --> 00:07:15,060
Next we zoom out the trace further.

54
00:07:17,280 --> 00:07:20,360
Here we have a trace of half a second per division.

55
00:07:25,970 --> 00:07:27,950
Here, half a second per division.

56
00:07:31,090 --> 00:07:33,210
We extend the trace.

57
00:07:34,410 --> 00:07:37,170
Up to two seconds per division.

58
00:07:40,240 --> 00:07:46,000
Now the device will reconfigure for low-frequency signals.

59
00:07:47,580 --> 00:07:50,980
And we see the next synchronization moment.

60
00:07:52,760 --> 00:08:00,540
This is the low-frequency component of space in this region where I live.

61
00:08:02,020 --> 00:08:09,080
Now we'll determine the frequency of space.

62
00:08:10,740 --> 00:08:16,540
We press pause and

63
00:08:20,310 --> 00:08:25,810
switch the device to cursor change mode.

64
00:08:28,310 --> 00:08:29,690
Manual.

65
00:08:30,250 --> 00:08:32,390
We see two markers have appeared.

66
00:08:42,330 --> 00:08:47,430
We move cursor A to the middle of the wave.

67
00:08:48,430 --> 00:08:53,210
We move cursor B also to the middle of the wave.

68
00:08:55,390 --> 00:08:58,590
This way we'll be determining the period of the oscillation.

69
00:08:59,990 --> 00:09:00,630
Let's see.

70
00:09:00,630 --> 00:09:10,870
The frequency is 235.8 MHz.

71
00:09:12,110 --> 00:09:17,670
That is, the frequency of these oscillations is 0.23 Hz.

72
00:09:19,410 --> 00:09:24,350
This coil synchronized with this frequency.

73
00:09:25,830 --> 00:09:28,650
Without synchronization, a gain is impossible.

74
00:09:30,350 --> 00:09:38,050
The coil cannot take energy from the generator, accordingly it cannot add more.

75
00:09:38,130 --> 00:09:40,990
But we're recording a larger current.

76
00:09:42,150 --> 00:09:48,050
So what'll happen if we reset our tuning.

77
00:09:50,270 --> 00:09:53,170
Now we'll return our signal.

78
00:09:58,210 --> 00:10:09,830
We brought back our signal and, say, with the generator we switch it to frequency mode and start detuning.

79
00:10:13,340 --> 00:10:15,280
Now we'll bring back what was.

80
00:10:18,820 --> 00:10:30,680
We brought back our 23.5 division and, for example, let's nudge by 300 Hz.

81
00:10:32,380 --> 00:10:34,200
We see, the current dropped.

82
00:10:36,610 --> 00:10:39,000
Let's nudge the frequency lower still.

83
00:10:42,160 --> 00:10:45,020
We see, there's practically no current.

84
00:10:48,660 --> 00:10:57,520
We can move higher or lower from our tuning and we see that there's no current.

85
00:10:59,320 --> 00:11:09,100
But now, if let's say at this frequency we hook up our ammeter, we'll be recording a larger current.

86
00:11:09,720 --> 00:11:16,940
In particular, we see that the tuning has slipped and the voltage amplitude on the output coil has also dropped.

87
00:11:18,100 --> 00:11:23,780
Now we'll switch the ammeter to the signal generator.

88
00:11:24,980 --> 00:11:26,080
Switching.

89
00:11:27,440 --> 00:11:34,280
We see that

90
00:11:38,810 --> 00:11:49,410
the current readings from the signal generator have stayed unchanged.

91
00:11:49,910 --> 00:11:58,050
The same 14 divisions, but with the frequency slipping, as we saw, the current in the system dropped significantly.

92
00:11:59,290 --> 00:12:07,450
These capacitors with respect to the output coil's inductance are not resonant.

93
00:12:11,430 --> 00:12:31,130
And this is the type of tuning that needs to be done for this system to start giving more than what we pump into it with this low-voltage drive, the push-pull-type generator.
